      body: `<div class="quick-facts"><h3>Quick Facts: Thailand</h3><ul><li><strong>Capital:</strong> Bangkok</li><li><strong>Currency:</strong> Thai Baht (THB). EUR1 ≈ THB38</li><li><strong>Flight time from Europe:</strong> 10–12 hours (one stop via Gulf or Asia)</li><li><strong>Main airports:</strong> Suvarnabhumi (BKK) and Don Mueang (DMK) — Bangkok; Chiang Mai (CNX); Phuket (HKT); Koh Samui (USM)</li><li><strong>Language:</strong> Thai. English spoken in tourist areas and hotels</li><li><strong>Best months:</strong> November–April (most regions); May–October (north and less-visited areas)</li><li><strong>Daily budget:</strong> EUR45–80 (mid-range); EUR100+ (comfort)</li><li><strong>Visa:</strong> Visa-on-arrival or e-visa; most EU nationals receive 30 days free on arrival</li></ul></div>

<p>Bangkok has become, in the taxonomy of long-haul travel, what Paris is to European city breaks — a shorthand for the destination rather than a description of it. The Thailand most visitors experience is BKK arrivals, Sukhumvit hotel corridor, a budget flight south to a beach. That itinerary is real, and it is worth the journey. It is also approximately 10% of what Thailand actually contains. The remaining 90% — the mountainous north, the less-visited gulf islands, the ancient Lanna kingdom cities, the limestone karst hinterland — rewards travelers who understand that a domestic flight from Suvarnabhumi costs less than a restaurant dinner and changes the entire equation.</p>

<h2>Bangkok: Three Days, Done Properly</h2>

<p>Suvarnabhumi (BKK) handles international arrivals. Don Mueang (DMK), 30km north, handles budget carriers for domestic connections. This is not a minor operational detail — knowing which airport your onward flight departs from before you land is the difference between a smooth connection and a chaotic one. The Airport Rail Link runs from Suvarnabhumi to central Bangkok in 30 minutes; taxis from DMK run 250–350 THB to the city centre depending on traffic, which is genuinely variable.</p>

<h3>Where to Stay in Bangkok</h3>
<p>Sukhumvit is the default and suits travelers who want BTS Skytrain access and international dining. For a better Bangkok experience, consider the Riverside area — quieter, architecturally more interesting, with easy Chao Phraya Express boat access to the temple circuit. The Silom–Sathorn corridor offers a middle ground: business-district efficiency with better restaurant density than Sukhumvit's tourist strip.</p>

<h3>Bangkok's Non-Negotiable Experiences</h3>
<p>Wat Pho (the Temple of the Reclining Buddha) and the Grand Palace circuit are genuine world-class sites, not merely obligatory. Go early — by 7:30am the light is good and the crowds are thin. Jay Fai, the Michelin-starred street cook on Mahachai Road, has been making her crab omelette over charcoal on the pavement since before the award arrived and has not changed the method since. A meal costs 1,000–2,000 THB and requires a reservation; it is worth both. Yaowarat — Bangkok's Chinatown — comes alive after dark. The roasted duck vendors on Yaowarat Road and the durian sellers under the archways operate at a pace and intensity that recalibrates your understanding of what a food street can actually be.</p>

<h2>Chiang Mai and the North: Thailand's Cultural Core</h2>

<p>Chiang Mai (CNX) is 90 minutes from Bangkok on AirAsia or Thai Airways — under EUR40 return booked in advance — and it unlocks a part of Thailand the south-focused tourist economy largely ignores. The city was the capital of the Lanna Kingdom; its moat-encircled old town contains over 300 temples, several of which are active monastic communities rather than set-piece attractions. The Sunday Walking Street on Wualai Road is one of Southeast Asia's more honest night markets: locally produced silverwork, textiles, and food at prices that have not been adjusted for tourist sensitivity.</p>

<h3>Where to Stay in Chiang Mai</h3>
<p>Inside the moat, the Nimman Road neighbourhood has become the city's design district — independent cafes, boutique hotels, and a walkable density that makes it the most liveable base in the city. The Old City itself (within the moat) suits travelers who want proximity to the temple circuit. Avoid the riverside area north of the city centre; the setting is attractive but the logistics add unnecessary travel time.</p>

<h3>Doi Inthanon: The Insider Move</h3>
<p>Most northern Thailand itineraries miss this entirely. Doi Inthanon National Park — Thailand's highest peak at 2,565 metres, one hour south of Chiang Mai — is extraordinary in late November. The summit is cool enough for frost at dawn, the rhododendrons are in partial bloom, and the birdlife exceeds 300 species, including endemics found nowhere else in Thailand. Most visitors are day-trippers from the city. The overnight camp near the summit, available through the national park, puts you in the forest before the coaches arrive and provides the kind of morning that justifies the detour.</p>

<h2>The Islands: Which One, When</h2>

<p>Thailand's island geography is divided by two separate coastlines with different weather systems. Understanding this before booking avoids the specific frustration of arriving in Koh Samui during its wet season because the brochure said "Thailand is sunny in December."</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Andaman Coast (Phuket, Krabi, Koh Lanta, Koh Phi Phi):</strong> Best November–April. The dry season here is the wet season on the Gulf side. Phuket (HKT) has direct international connections; it is also the most commercialised island in the country. Krabi and Koh Lanta offer the same limestone karst scenery with meaningfully less tourist infrastructure.</li>
  <li><strong>Gulf of Thailand (Koh Samui, Koh Phangan, Koh Tao):</strong> Best February–October. December and January bring unpredictable rain on this coast. Koh Tao is the dive training capital of Southeast Asia — PADI open water certification costs a fraction of European prices.</li>
  <li><strong>Less-visited alternatives:</strong> Koh Yao Noi (between Phuket and Krabi, accessible by longtail boat) and Koh Lipe (far south, near the Malaysian border) offer the physical setting of the more famous islands without the infrastructure that has developed around them.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Best Time to Visit Thailand</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>November–February:</strong> Peak season for most of the country. Reliable dry weather coast-to-coast, lower humidity, cooler nights in the north. Fares and accommodation run 20–35% above annual averages; book 16–20 weeks ahead for December and January.</li>
  <li><strong>March–May:</strong> Hot and increasingly humid. Good for travelers focused on the north (where the heat is more bearable at elevation) and those avoiding peak-season pricing.</li>
  <li><strong>May–October:</strong> Green season. The Andaman Coast receives heavy rainfall June–October; the north is lush and visually impressive. Significant discounts on accommodation; fares from Europe are at annual lows in this window.</li>
  <li><strong>Songkran (Thai New Year, mid-April):</strong> The country's most significant festival — and a genuinely extraordinary experience if you're prepared for the water festival chaos. Book well ahead; domestic travel is overwhelmed.</li>
</ul>

<p>[See our latest flight deals to Thailand]</p>

<h2>Flights to Thailand from Europe</h2>

<p>Bangkok (BKK) is the primary gateway from Europe. Phuket (HKT) has direct connections from several European hubs, particularly on charter carriers, which can be significantly cheaper for island-focused itineraries. The most competitive scheduled fares route via Gulf hubs — Qatar Airways through Doha, Emirates through Dubai, Thai Airways through various Asian connections. Journey times run 11–13 hours one-stop. Turkish Airlines via Istanbul is consistently worth including in searches; their Bangkok fares regularly undercut Gulf carrier pricing by EUR50–120.</p>

<p>The open-jaw structure is correct for most Thailand itineraries: fly into Bangkok (BKK), exit from Phuket (HKT) or Chiang Mai (CNX). Search as multi-city — the fare difference from a return is typically EUR30–80, which is a reasonable price for an itinerary that eliminates a domestic backtrack and adds meaningful geographic range. The 8–12 week booking window is the consistent sweet spot for shoulder season travel; for December and January, 16–20 weeks is the minimum before preferred routings sell through.</p>

<h2>Getting Around Thailand</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Domestic flights:</strong> AirAsia and Nok Air connect Bangkok to all major cities and islands for EUR25–60 return booked in advance. Always check both BKK airports for domestic departures.</li>
  <li><strong>Trains:</strong> The State Railway network is slow but scenic and dramatically cheaper than flights. The overnight train from Bangkok to Chiang Mai (10 hours, sleeper class available) is a genuine experience and worth doing once.</li>
  <li><strong>Grab:</strong> Works in Bangkok, Chiang Mai, and Phuket. Essential for predictable urban pricing.</li>
  <li><strong>Island transfers:</strong> Ferry schedules to most gulf islands run twice daily. Book the morning departure — afternoon services are more prone to weather cancellations.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Cultural Etiquette</h2>
<ul>
  <li>The monarchy is not a subject for casual commentary. Lèse-majesté laws carry real legal consequences.</li>
  <li>Remove shoes at all temples and many guesthouses. Dress code at major temples requires covered shoulders and knees — a sarong is available for hire at the Grand Palace entrance.</li>
  <li>The Thai greeting (a slight bow with hands pressed together) is always appropriate; a handshake is equally accepted in urban contexts.</li>
  <li>Avoid touching anyone's head — it is considered the most sacred part of the body — and do not point the soles of your feet at people or Buddha images.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Budget Expectations</h2>
<p>Thailand remains excellent value relative to its quality and geographic range. A mid-range daily budget — air-conditioned hotel in a good location, restaurant meals including occasional splurges, local transport — runs EUR50–80. The gap between budget and comfort travel is wide here: a genuinely good hotel in central Bangkok costs EUR80–120 per night; a clean, well-located guesthouse costs EUR20–35. Street food remains the best food in the country at most price points — a bowl of khao soi in Chiang Mai from a market stall will beat the equivalent in a hotel restaurant every time.</p>

<p>[See our latest flight deals to Thailand]</p>

<h2>FAQ: Thailand Travel</h2>

<h3>Do EU citizens need a visa for Thailand?</h3>
<p>Most EU nationals receive 30 days visa-on-arrival at no charge. Thailand introduced a 60-day visa-on-arrival for several European nationalities in 2024 — check the current list before travel, as the policy has been updated multiple times. For stays beyond 30 days, a tourist visa applied in advance provides 60 days with one extension possible.</p>

<h3>Is Thailand safe for solo female travelers?</h3>
<p>Yes, with the standard caveats that apply across Southeast Asia. Thailand has a well-established solo travel infrastructure, particularly in Chiang Mai and the backpacker island circuit. The main risks are traffic (motorbike accidents are the leading cause of tourist injury), drink spiking at some tourist-area bars, and scam operations targeting new arrivals in Bangkok. None of these is exceptional by regional standards; awareness is sufficient mitigation for most.</p>

<h3>What is the best island in Thailand for first-time visitors?</h3>
<p>Krabi or Koh Lanta over Phuket, if visiting November–April. The limestone karst scenery is equivalent; the atmosphere is considerably less commercialised. Koh Tao for divers at any level — the water clarity, marine life diversity, and certification cost make it one of the best dive learning environments in the world.</p>

<h3>How far is Chiang Mai from Bangkok?</h3>
<p>700km by road; 90 minutes by domestic flight. AirAsia and Thai Smile both serve the route multiple times daily. Booked two weeks or more ahead, fares run 800–1,500 THB (EUR20–40) one way. The overnight train takes 10–12 hours and costs 700–1,200 THB for a sleeper berth — a legitimate experience if the schedule allows.</p>`
