      body: `<div class="quick-facts"><h3>Quick Facts: Oman</h3><ul><li><strong>Capital:</strong> Muscat</li><li><strong>Currency:</strong> Omani Rial (OMR). EUR1 ≈ OMR0.42 (the Rial is pegged high; Oman is not cheap)</li><li><strong>Flight time from Europe:</strong> 6–8 hours (direct or one stop via Gulf)</li><li><strong>Main airport:</strong> Muscat International (MCT)</li><li><strong>Language:</strong> Arabic. English widely spoken in tourism and business contexts</li><li><strong>Best months:</strong> October–April</li><li><strong>Daily budget:</strong> EUR70–120 (mid-range self-drive); EUR150+ (guided/comfort)</li><li><strong>Visa:</strong> E-visa required for most EU nationals. OMR20, processed in 24–48 hours online</li></ul></div>

<p>Oman is what the Arabian Peninsula looked like before the oil economy reshaped it — and, more precisely, what that economy looks like when it chooses restraint. While its neighbours have urbanised at a pace that occasionally outran meaning, Oman developed more carefully. The Hajar Mountains still dominate Muscat's skyline by law; no building may exceed their height within the capital. The frankincense trade that connected this coastline to Rome, India, and China for two millennia remains active in the Muttrah Souq. The country rewards travelers who arrive with serious intent in ways the Gulf's more publicised destinations have largely stopped being able to, and it does so at fares from Europe that continue to understate what is waiting at the other end.</p>

<p>Oman is not a destination that announces itself loudly. It accumulates. By the third day, the combination of physical landscape, cultural coherence, and hospitality that predates the tourism industry by centuries has produced something difficult to articulate and easy to remember.</p>

<h2>Muscat: The Capital That Earns Its Reputation Quietly</h2>

<p>Land at Muscat International (MCT) — a genuinely pleasant airport, efficiently run, with Oman Air operating a modern long-haul fleet — and the first thing the city does is not shout at you. The drive from MCT to the Muttrah Corniche, where most visitors base themselves for the capital section of an Omani itinerary, takes 35–45 minutes and passes the Hajar Mountains coming down to the Gulf of Oman, white-painted buildings stepping up the hillside, no billboard advertising on the road into town. It is an unusually considered arrival.</p>

<h3>The Muttrah Souq: The Correct First Evening</h3>
<p>The Muttrah Souq is not a tourist market in the way Dubai's Gold Souq has become. It is a working commercial space where frankincense resin, silver Khanjar daggers (the traditional curved Omani blade), dried limes, Indian Ocean textiles, and imported Iranian ceramics trade alongside each other in an arrangement that has functioned in some form since the Silk Road was operational. Buy frankincense — you will find better quality and more honest pricing here than at the airport — and understand that the Omani tradition of burning it at home every evening is not ceremonial. It is simply what the houses smell like.</p>

<h3>The Sultan Qaboos Grand Mosque</h3>
<p>One of the most architecturally significant mosques built in the 20th century — 300,000 individual pieces of handmade Swarovski crystal in the main chandelier, a single-carpet prayer hall covering 4,343 square metres woven in Iran over four years — and open to non-Muslim visitors Saturday through Thursday mornings until 11am. Dress code is strict: women require full abaya coverage including head covering; men in long trousers and covered shoulders. Bring both and enter without hesitation. The scale and craft are extraordinary by any standard.</p>

<h2>Beyond Muscat: The Five Essential Experiences</h2>

<h3>1. Wadi Shab and Wadi Bani Khalid</h3>
<p>The wadi system — seasonal riverbeds carved into the Hajar limestone over millennia — is Oman's defining natural landscape. Wadi Shab, two hours southeast of Muscat, requires a short boat crossing (OMR1) followed by a 45-minute walk through palm-shaded gorges to a series of turquoise plunge pools fed by a waterfall. Swimming here, in mountain water under limestone walls, is one of the Gulf region's genuinely exceptional natural experiences. Wadi Bani Khalid, slightly further south, is more accessible by car and equally beautiful; it suits travelers with less time or mobility constraints.</p>

<h3>2. Nizwa and the Interior</h3>
<p>Nizwa — two hours southwest of Muscat — was the capital of the Imamate of Oman and remains the cultural heart of the interior. The Nizwa Fort, a 17th-century circular tower dominating the old town, and the adjacent Nizwa Souq (particularly the Friday morning goat market, which is neither curated nor touristic) constitute the most authentic encounter with Omani interior culture available within a day trip of the capital. The drive through the Al Hajar Mountains between Muscat and Nizwa — via the Fanja–Bidbid road — is worth taking the longer Al Kamil route for the mountain scenery alone.</p>

<h3>3. Jebel Akhdar: The Green Mountain</h3>
<p>At 2,980 metres, Jebel Akhdar ("the Green Mountain") sits above Nizwa and receives enough rainfall to support rose cultivation — the Damask roses grown in the villages of Al Ain and Ash Sharayjah are distilled into rose water sold throughout the Gulf. The plateau is cool even in summer, the village terraces are intact, and the views from the Al Ayn ruin village across the wadi to the opposite escarpment are among the most photographically productive in the country. A 4WD vehicle is required above a certain point on the ascent; car hire at Muscat airport is the most practical approach.</p>

<h3>4. Sur and Ras Al Jinz: Turtle Season</h3>
<p>Sur, on Oman's eastern cape, was once one of the Arabian Peninsula's great dhow-building centres. Traditional wooden dhow construction continues at the Sur Dhow Factory — one of very few places in the world where this craft remains commercially active. Thirty kilometres south, Ras Al Jinz Turtle Reserve is one of the world's most significant loggerhead and green turtle nesting sites. Nightly guided walks (booking essential, OMR25–35) allow visitors to observe nesting females and, in season, hatching. The season runs year-round but peaks June–September for nesting and November–February for hatching.</p>

<h3>5. Salalah and the Khareef Season</h3>
<p>Salalah — in the southern Dhofar region, 1,000km from Muscat — receives its own monsoon, the khareef, between June and September. During this period, while the rest of the Gulf bakes under 45°C, Salalah receives mist and rain from the Indian Ocean and the Qara Mountains turn improbably, brilliantly green. The contrast — a lush, cool, cloud-covered plateau 90 minutes by Oman Air from the dusty capital — is one of the Arabian Peninsula's more quietly extraordinary experiences. Frankincense trees grow wild here. The region was the Dhofar Sultanate before merger with Oman; its culture, dialect, and food are distinct from the north.</p>

<h2>Best Time to Visit Oman</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>October–November:</strong> Post-summer heat, pre-peak season. Temperatures in Muscat drop to manageable 28–35°C. The best shoulder season window; fares and accommodation are reasonable.</li>
  <li><strong>December–February:</strong> Peak season. Muscat temperatures run 20–27°C — genuinely pleasant. Christmas and New Year carry premium pricing. January and February are arguably the best months in the country: comfortable everywhere, mountain roads clear, turtles hatching at Ras Al Jinz.</li>
  <li><strong>March–April:</strong> Warming but still workable. Good for the wadis and mountain areas before the heat makes low-elevation activity uncomfortable.</li>
  <li><strong>May–September:</strong> Extreme heat in the north (40–45°C in Muscat). Only viable for Salalah during the khareef (June–September), where conditions are actively pleasant.</li>
</ul>

<p>[See our latest flight deals to Oman]</p>

<h2>Flights to Oman from Europe</h2>

<p>Muscat (MCT) is served directly from London (Gatwick and Heathrow), Frankfurt, Paris, Amsterdam, Vienna, Zurich, and a growing number of European secondary cities by Oman Air, which operates a modern Boeing 787 Dreamliner and Airbus A330 fleet. Direct journey times from Western Europe run 7–8 hours — one of the more manageable long-haul options available from the European market. One-stop alternatives via Gulf hubs add connecting time but occasionally produce better pricing. Low-cost carrier fares occasionally appear on the MCT corridor from budget-oriented hubs; these are worth tracking on Google Flights and FlyWell alerts.</p>

<p>Oman remains underbooked relative to its quality, which means booking windows are more forgiving than equivalent Gulf destinations. Six to eight weeks of lead time is generally sufficient outside the Christmas–New Year window, which requires 14–16 weeks minimum. Oman Air's promotional inventory — which appears several times annually — produces some of the best value MENA fares from Europe when it surfaces. FlyWell publishes these windows as they appear.</p>

<h2>Getting Around Oman</h2>
<p>Self-drive is the correct approach for most Omani itineraries. The road network outside the capital is excellent; distances are large but traffic outside Muscat is minimal. A standard saloon car suffices for the Muscat–Nizwa–Sur circuit and most Jebel Akhdar access roads; a 4WD is necessary for Jebel Akhdar's upper reaches and any wadi driving off tarmac. Car hire at Muscat airport runs EUR30–60 per day for a saloon; 4WDs run EUR70–100. Petrol is heavily subsidised — a full tank costs approximately EUR10.</p>

<h2>Cultural Etiquette</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Oman is a conservative Muslim country. Dress modestly outside beach resorts and hotel pools: covered shoulders and knees for both men and women in souqs, markets, and religious sites.</li>
  <li>Ramadan brings restricted food and beverage service during daylight hours in public. Tourists are not expected to fast but should eat and drink discreetly outside designated areas.</li>
  <li>Photography of people requires permission, particularly of women. Of landscapes, buildings, and markets generally, it is welcomed.</li>
  <li>Omani hospitality culture — the offer of coffee (qahwa, cardamom-spiced, poured from a dallah) and dates — is a genuine social institution. Accept it whenever offered; declining is considered impolite.</li>
</ul>

<h2>FAQ: Oman Travel</h2>

<h3>Is Oman safe to visit?</h3>
<p>Oman is one of the safest countries in the Middle East and one of the safest destinations globally by most measured indices. Crime against tourists is extremely rare. The country has maintained political stability under Sultan Haitham bin Tariq, who succeeded Sultan Qaboos in 2020, and Oman's non-alignment in regional conflicts has preserved its security environment. Solo female travel is well-established and generally comfortable.</p>

<h3>How many days do I need in Oman?</h3>
<p>Seven days covers the Muscat–Nizwa–Wadi Shab–Sur circuit properly with a day on Jebel Akhdar. Ten days allows Salalah to be added (domestic flight with Oman Air, EUR60–90 return). Two weeks permits a more relaxed pace through all regions, including extended time in the Hajar Mountains.</p>

<h3>Do I need a 4WD in Oman?</h3>
<p>For the main tourist circuit (Muscat, Nizwa, Wadi Shab, Sur), no. For Jebel Akhdar above the checkpoint, yes — and the checkpoint will turn back standard cars. For off-road wadi driving or any route marked as "4WD only" on maps, yes. When in doubt, upgrade at the airport; the cost difference is modest and the access it provides is significant.</p>

<h3>Can I drink alcohol in Oman?</h3>
<p>Alcohol is available in licensed hotel bars and restaurants and in duty-free at MCT airport. It is not sold in supermarkets or souqs and is not consumed in public spaces. The practical reality for most tourists is that alcohol is available at dinner and in hotels without restriction — it simply requires being in the right venue.</p>`
